{"title_page": "The Hills (song)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{short description|2015 single by The Weeknd}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = The Hills\n| cover      = The Weeknd - The Hills.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[The Weeknd]]\n| album      = [[Beauty Behind the Madness]]\n| released   = {{Start date|2015|5|27}}\n| format     = [[Music download|Digital download]]\n| recorded   = 2014\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      =\n* [[Alternative R&B]]\n* [[Trap music|trap]]\n| length     =\n* 4:04 {{small|(album and single version)}}\n* 3:55 {{small|(video version)}}\n| label      =\n* [[XO (record label)|XO]]\n* [[Republic Records|Republic]]\n| writer     =\n* [[The Weeknd|Abel Tesfaye]]\n* Emmanuel Nickerson\n* [[Illangelo|Carlo Montagnese]]\n* [[Belly (rapper)|Ahmad Balshe]]\n| producer   =\n* [[Mano]]\n* Illangelo\n| prev_title = [[Earned It]]\n| prev_year  = 2014\n| next_title = [[Can't Feel My Face]]\n| next_year  = 2015\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|yzTuBuRdAyA|\"The Hills\"}}\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''The Hills'''\" is a song by Canadian singer [[The Weeknd]]. It was released on May 27, 2015 as the second [[single (music)|single]] from his second studio album, ''[[Beauty Behind the Madness]]'' (2015).<ref name=\"itunes\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/the-hills-single/id999009844 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150611041515/https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/the-hills-single/id999009844 |archivedate=June 11, 2015 |url-status=live |title=The Hills - Single by The Weeknd|publisher=[[iTunes]] (US)|accessdate=June 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\"The Hills\" was a critical success, appearing on several year-end lists. In the singer's native Canada, the song peaked at number one. In the United States it also reached number one on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]], [[List of Billboard Hot 100 number-one singles of 2015|replacing]] his own \"[[Can't Feel My Face]]\". The song also made the top 10 in the United Kingdom, Ireland, Germany, Australia, and New Zealand. It reached the top 20 in Denmark and Sweden while reaching the top 40 in The Netherlands, Norway, and Switzerland. The Hills recently was certified Diamond in 2019. A music video for the song was released on May 27, 2015. It was directed by Grant Singer.\n\n==Composition==\nThe song is written in the key of [[C minor]] in [[Time signature|common time]] with a [[tempo]] of 113 [[beats per minute]].  The vocals in the song span from C3 to E{{Flat}}5.<ref>{{Cite web|title = The Hills|url = http://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtd.asp?ppn=MN0155263|website = www.musicnotes.com|access-date = January 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nProducer Illangelo stated \u201dI\u2019m very optimistic and positive with anything I put my energy towards, so for me, Abel\u2019s success now is what I imagined it always should have been. \u2018The Hills\u2019 was an opportunity for us to go back to the classical, original the Weeknd moments of our first mixtapes that I co\u2013produced and mixed in their entirety, and then bringing that into a new context, with a pop arrangement and chords in a faster tempo. It's the perfect marriage of that.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Tingen|first1=Paul|title=Inside Track: The Weeknd|url=http://www.soundonsound.com/techniques/inside-track-weeknd|website=Soundonsound|accessdate=November 24, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Quote box |quoted=true |bgcolor=#bbccff |salign=right |width=240px |align=right | quote =That\u2019s probably the most important song in my career because it is the Weeknd and the irony being it was the most successful song that I had ever done.  | source =\u2013 The Weeknd on \"The Hills\"<ref name=\"Kikizo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-ca-ms-weeknd-grammys-conversation-20160211-htmlstory.html |title=How the Weeknd got his revenge and became one of the biggest pop stars |publisher=LA Times |date= |accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref>}}\n\"The Hills\" received critical acclaim, with most reviewers praising The Weeknd's return to form after his pop-oriented direction with \"[[Earned It]]\". James Shotwell of Under the Gun wrote that the single fit well within Abel's prior output, but that \"Abel\u2019s ability to create something altogether hypnotic regardless of production never ceases to amaze.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.underthegunreview.net/2015/05/27/the-weeknd-drops-the-hills/|title=The Weeknd Drops 'The Hills'|work=Under the Gun Review|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170723124400/http://underthegunreview.net/2015/05/27/the-weeknd-drops-the-hills/|archivedate=July 23, 2017}}</ref> Brian Mansfield of ''[[USA Today]]'' noted that \"when a song takes its hook from a horror film \u2014 [[Wes Craven]]'s 1977 cult classic ''[[The Hills Have Eyes (1977 film)|The Hills Have Eyes]]'' \u2014 you know there's bound to be trouble.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/reviews/2015/06/02/weeknd-the-hills-song-of-the-week/28299897|title=Song of the Week: The Weeknd's 'The Hills'|date=June 2, 2015|work=USA TODAY}}</ref>\n\nIn an analytical piece for ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'', Hannah Giorgis called \"The Hills\" \"a dark, almost discordant meditation on lust, drugs, and fame\" while noting that \"to those familiar with his repertoire, the only twist in 'The Hills' is how it ends: as the final chords fade, a woman\u2019s voice, syrupy and sedate, closes with a lullaby of sorts\u2014not in English, but in Amharic, the primary language of Ethiopia and the Weeknd\u2019s own native tongue.\" She goes on to trace the song's melodic and lyrical origins to the Ethiopian diaspora. She continues, writing that \"the familiarity of Tesfaye\u2019s strained vibrato makes him the inheritor of musical legacies that Abyssinia has birthed for generations...\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/thepitch/793-the-weeknds-east-african-roots/|title=The Weeknd's East African Roots|work=Pitchfork}}</ref> In a review for ''[[The New York Post]]'', Hardeep Phull wrote that \"The 'Fifty Shades of Grey' fans who were turned on to [The] Weeknd (real name Abel Tesfaye) through his hit 'Earned It' are in for a shock, because he is in brilliantly sinister form on his new track.\" Continuing, Phull goes on to say that \"When it comes to being a Don Juan with a dark side, this guy makes Christian Grey look like [[Ned Flanders]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2015/06/01/the-weeknd-gets-sinister-and-more-music-reviews/|title=The Weeknd gets sinister and more music reviews|work=New York Post}}</ref>\n\n''[[Rolling Stone]]'' ranked \"The Hills\" at number 11 on its year-end list to find the 50 best songs of 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/50-best-songs-of-2015-20151203/titus-andronicus-dimed-out-20151203|title=50 Best Songs of 2015|publisher=Billboard.com}}</ref> The same magazine also included \"Earned It\" and \"Can't Feel My Face\" on the same list. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' ranked \"The Hills\" at number 10 on its year-end list for 2015: \"Number one hits aren't supposed to be this sonically adventurous and dark, but The Weeknd can do no wrong in 2015. There's barely a pop hook to speak of here\u2014\u2014just a beguiling, harrowing soundscape that's impossible to forget.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/events/year-in-music-2015/6806155/billboard-25-best-songs-critics-picks|title=Billboard 25 Best Songs of 2015: Critics' Picks|publisher=Billboard.com}}</ref> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' named \"The Hills\" the fifth-best song of 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/4132832/top-10-best-songs-2/|title=Best Songs of 2015|publisher=Time|accessdate=January 14, 2016}}</ref> The ''[[Village Voice]]'' ranked \"The Hills\" at number 22 on their annual year-end critic's poll; \"Can't Feel My Face\" was ranked at number three on the same poll.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://furia.com/pjs/table_song_2015_total.html|title=Pazz & Jop Statistics|publisher=The Village Voice|accessdate=January 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe song was also the subject of copyright infringement, as Cutting Edge Music alleged that the bassline was featured in the score for ''[[The Machine (film)|The Machine]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=THE WEEKND SUED OVER 'THE HILLS'|url=http://www.tmz.com/2015/12/09/the-weeknd-the-hills-lawsuit/|website=Tmz|accessdate=May 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\nIn the United States, \"The Hills\" entered the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] at number 20 for the chart dated June 13, 2015; it was the week's highest debut.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/2015-06-13 |title=The Hot 100: The Week of June 13, 2015 |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |accessdate=June 13, 2015}}</ref> Its debut was overwhelmingly powered by first-week [[Music download|digital download]] sales of 109,000 copies and 5.2 million domestic [[Streaming media|streams]], aided by the simultaneous premiere of its [[music video]] on the single's release date.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6590075/weeknd-hills-top-10-debut-hot-rb-songs |title=The Weeknd's 'The Hills' Makes Top 10 Debut on Hot R&B Songs |last=Mendizabal |first=Amaya |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |date=June 4, 2015 |accessdate=June 13, 2015}}</ref> The following week, the single declined by one position but earned the largest gain in streams on the chart<!-- this is not mentioned to start a blow-by-blow recounting of every single chart week [don't do that] but to show the influence of the various chart components on its performance -->.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/2015-06-20 |title=The Hot 100: The Week of June 20, 2015 |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |accessdate=June 13, 2015}}</ref> It has since become The Weeknd's second number-one single in the United States on the issue dated October 3, 2015, replacing the singer's own \"Can't Feel My Face\", becoming the first artist since [[Taylor Swift]] to replace themselves at the top spot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6700789/the-weeknd-replaces-himself-hot-100-the-hills-no-1|title=The Weeknd replaces himself at No. 1 with 'The Hills'|publisher=Billboard.com}}</ref> \"The Hills\" spent six consecutive weeks at number one before being replaced by [[Adele]]{{'}}s \"[[Hello (Adele song)|Hello]]\" on the issue dated of November 14, 2015. It remained in the chart's top ten for twenty-one consecutive weeks before finally dropping out on January 16, 2016 and also ending The Weeknd's 45-consecutive weeks in the top 10.{{citation needed|date=October 2015}} As of June 2016, \"The Hills\" has sold <!-- PLEASE DON'T UPDATE THE SALES AMOUNT UNLESS THE REFERENCE IS ALSO UPDATED -->2,946,000 copies in the country.<ref name=us_sales>{{cite news|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160705145725/http://www.defjampromo.com/files/2009/10/BB-Digital-Songs-Chart-Wk.-Ending-6-16-16.pdf|title=Nielsen SoundScan charts \u2013 Digital Songs \u2013 Week Ending: 06/06/2016|publisher=[[Nielsen SoundScan]]|url=http://www.defjampromo.com:80/files/2009/10/BB-Digital-Songs-Chart-Wk.-Ending-6-16-16.pdf|archivedate=July 5, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn the UK, \"The Hills\" entered the [[UK Singles Chart]] at 51, for the week ending June 6, 2015. The following week, it went to 30. The following week, it fell to 35. Three weeks later, it had fallen out of the top 40, but the following week it re-entered at 35 and spent 7 more weeks hovering without going higher than 31. For the week ending September 10, 2015, it climbed from 35 to 29. For 5 more weeks, it climbed, reaching 23, before rocketing to number 5 the week later. On the week ending October 29, 2015, it reached number 3 on its 20th week, being held off by [[Perfect (One Direction song)|Perfect]] by One Direction (at number 2) and [[Turn the Music Louder (Rumble)]] by [[KDA (DJ)|KDA]] (at number 1). It spent 7 weeks altogether in the top 10 and 12 in the top 20. It managed to spend longer a lot longer in the top 40 (39 weeks) and 57 in the top 100. It spent 51 weeks in the top 100 in its first run. It was number 25 on the end of year chart.\n\n==Music video==\nThe music video for \"The Hills\" was directed by Grant Singer. It was uploaded to [[YouTube]] on May 27, 2015. As of December 2019, the video has been viewed over 1.4 billion times, placing it in the 100 most viewed YouTube videos. The video begins showing a wrecked car that has flipped over, and the reason it flipped is unknown. The Weeknd is seen crawling out of the car before helping two women to get out. As the song progresses, The Weeknd is seen walking by himself down South June Street in Los Angeles, and at the beginning of the second chorus, the wrecked car explodes behind him.<ref>https://globalfilmlocations.net/2017/04/24/the-weeknd-the-hills-filming-location/</ref> He occasionally is pushed repeatedly by one of the women from the car. At the end of the song, he enters an abandoned mansion, and goes upstairs to a room illuminated with red light. A man holding an [[Apple (symbolism)|apple]] sits waiting for him, next to two other women, and the video cuts to black.\n\nThe man from inside the mansion is [[The Mau-Mau's|Rick Wilder]], who also appears in both the \"Can't Feel My Face\" and \"Tell Your Friends\" music videos.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ducker|first1=Eric|title=How This Glam Rock OG Became the Weeknd\u2019s Video Muse|url=http://pitchfork.com/thepitch/917-how-this-glam-rock-og-became-the-weeknds-video-muse/|website=Pitchfork|accessdate=May 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAnother [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2fhjdtQDcOo music video] was filmed for the [[Eminem]] remix in collaboration with [[GoPro]] and United Realities, is a 360-degree [[virtual reality]] video in which The Weeknd is seen leaving a venue and heading to his limo. As the viewer changes the angles, it's shown that comets are raining down and the raining debris causing fiery explosions around the area. The car that's flipped over in the original music video is also in view. As he approaches his limousine, a fiery explosion consumes him.\n\n==Remixes and media use==\nOn October 10, 2015, two remixes of the song were released online. One featured American rapper [[Eminem]] and the other featured Trinidadian-American rapper [[Nicki Minaj]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/listen-to-both-eminem-and-nicki-minajs-remixes-of-the-weeknds-the-hills-news.18117.html | title=Listen To Both Eminem & Nicki Minaj's Remixes Of The Weeknd's \"The Hills\" | work=hotnewhiphop | accessdate=October 10, 2015}}</ref> The remix by Minaj was performed on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' along with The Weeknd. A virtual music video was made for the Eminem remix.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2fhjdtQDcOo | title=The Weeknd - The Hills remix feat. Eminem ( A Virtual Reality Experience) - YouTube}}</ref> American rapper [[Lil Wayne]] remixed the song for his mixtape ''[[No Ceilings 2]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/lil-waynes-no-ceilings-2-tracklist-revealed-news.18859.html | title=Lil Wayne's \"No Ceilings 2\" Tracklist Revealed | work=hotnewhiphop | date=November 26, 2015 | accessdate=December 8, 2015}}</ref> The song was also featured in ''[[Life in Pieces]]'' season 1, episode 21.\n\nOn August 9, 2016, another remix has also been released by the Belgian DJ duo, [[Dimitri Vegas & Like Mike]], as one of the free downloads of their \"Summer of Madness\" tracks.<ref name=\"Summer of Madness\">[http://www.summerofmadness.com/dvlmtracks/dwnltheweeknd.php?id=1275678935787375 \"SUMMER OF MADNESS\" by Dimitri Vegas & Like Mike]</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n* '''Digital download'''\n# \"The Hills\" (The Weeknd only) \u2013 3:55\n\n* '''Digital download \u2013 remixes'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itun.es/gb/zaaF-|title=iTunes - Music - The Hills (Remixes) - Single by The Weeknd|publisher=[[iTunes Store]] (GB)}}</ref>\n# \"The Hills\" (featuring Eminem) \u2013 4:23\n# \"The Hills\" (featuring Nicki Minaj) \u2013 4:02\n\n* '''Digital download \u2013 Remixes\n# \"The Hills\" ([[RL Grime]] Remix) \u2013 4:31\n# \"The Hills\" ([[Dimitri Vegas & Like Mike]] Remix) \u2014 5:55\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2015\u201316)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Australia|3|artist=The Weeknd|song=The Hills|accessdate=October 24, 2015|rowheader=true|refname=}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Australian Urban ([[ARIA Charts|ARIA]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ariacharts.com.au/chart/urban-singles |title=ARIA Australian Top 40 Urban Singles Chart |publisher=ARIA Charts |accessdate=October 24, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150823090939/http://www.ariacharts.com.au/chart/urban-singles |archivedate=August 23, 2015 }}</ref>\n| 3\n|-\n{{singlechart|Austria|31|artist=The Weeknd|song=The Hills|accessdate=October 22, 2015|rowheader=true|refname=}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|18|artist=The Weeknd|song=The Hills|accessdate=November 28, 2015|rowheader=true|refname=}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders Urban|3|artist=The Weeknd|song=The Hills|accessdate=November 20, 2015|rowheader=true|refname=}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Wallonia|18|artist=The Weeknd|song=The Hills|accessdate=January 30, 2016|rowheader=true|refname=}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canada|1|artist=The Weeknd|accessdate=October 20, 2015|rowheader=true|song=|refname=}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|CIS|14|artist=The Weeknd|song=The Hills|rowheader=true|songid=68470}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Czech Republic|12|year=2